  <notes>
    Spec.md line 332 labels ADR-019 as "SPE access" — that's a spec-side typo. The actual ADR-019 is ProblemDetails (RFC 7807). Both apply: SPE access (ADR-007 SpeFileStore facade) AND ProblemDetails (ADR-019) for error responses. This task cites both correctly.

    The streaming pattern: `ZipArchive(HttpContext.Response.Body, ZipArchiveMode.Create, leaveOpen: true)` enables true streaming — files are written to the response as they're downloaded from Graph, no full-file buffering. CRITICAL: detect total-failure BEFORE flushing response headers, because once headers are flushed you cannot return ProblemDetails. Pre-resolve all documentId → (driveId, itemId, fileName) lookups first; if all lookups fail, return ProblemDetails. If at least one resolves, begin streaming and handle per-download failures in the zip.

    Authorization scope: spec.md §Unresolved Questions notes "Bulk-download endpoint authorization scope — same policy as preview-url assumed; confirm with architecture if a separate policy is needed for bulk operations". Default to the preview-url policy; flag in PR description if architecture wants a separate bulk-scoped policy.

    Filename format: `documents-{matterIdOrBulk}-{timestamp}.zip`. If all documents share one matter (resolve from doc lookup), use that matter id; otherwise use literal "bulk". Timestamp ISO 8601 compact form e.g. `20260527T143022Z`.

    Placement Justification (binding per `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md` §10 + §A.1, owner-clarified at design layer per `spec.md §Owner Clarifications`):
    Bulk download belongs in the BFF, not the PCF. Reasons: (1) Client-side zip would buffer all file bytes in browser memory (500 docs × multi-MB = hundreds of MB → kill the tab); server-side streaming via `SpeFileStore.DownloadFileAsync` → `ZipArchive` over `HttpResponse.Body` keeps memory bounded regardless of selection size. (2) The endpoint requires the same auth scheme + Dataverse lookup + SPE app-only access as the existing `GET /api/documents/{documentId}/download` in `FileAccessEndpoints` — extending that BFF surface reuses identical infrastructure (no parallel auth in PCF). (3) Decision criteria from `bff-extensions.md` table: Q1 latency budget (YES — user-facing download), Q2 BFF-managed session/auth state (YES — JWT bearer + tenant claim validation), Q4 event-driven (NO — synchronous user wait), Q5 external-consumer facade (NO — internal PCF consumer). Three of four criteria favor BFF; the fourth doesn't apply. No new NuGet packages (uses BCL `System.IO.Compression.ZipArchive`); no new DI registrations (reuses `IDocumentDataverseService` + `SpeFileStore`); follows `MapDocumentsBulkEndpoints` feature-module extension pattern (ADR-010); endpoint-filter authorization mirrors `SemanticSearchAuthorizationFilter` shape (ADR-008).
  </notes>

